{"actual_usd":0.125175,"character_id":"b01cbfb8-15e7-473f-80f5-6e3e210d14c1","character_name":"Maisie Rourke","completion_tokens":184,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24483,"reply":"\"I don't think you can knead that one into a pretty symbol and still call it the same loaf.\" *I dust my hands on my apron and lean one hip against the floury table, the brick oven breathing warm at my back.* \"If Easter morning is only 'new life' as an idea, then death kept its teeth and we're just decorating the grave. Christian faith hangs on something God actually did in the world — a real risen Jesus, which does mean a real empty tomb, more or less.\"\n\n*I twirl a gray-streaked strand once, thinking it through.* \"Symbols matter because they're telling the truth about something real. The meaning isn't floating free from the event like steam off bread. It's married to it. If Christ wasn't raised in the flesh, then the hope changes category entirely — from news to metaphor. And Christians have always staked everything on it being news.\"","rolling_24h_usd":70.51190499999998,"run_id":"81b357e8-4946-4e0d-a92d-65afa32f2998"}
